In this survey, the scenario is complicated. The first man knocked into the bottle, the second man was trying to catch it, and the third man knocked the second man out of the way so the bottle ended up spilling on the floor. The first man was partially responsible for the bottle spilling, but the third man was more responsible because he stopped the second man from catching the bottle.

I'm not sure I've thought this through adequately, but what seemed to make an Agree response in some form most appropriate was the fact that the bottle was already falling and would have spilt but for the cited action.

The question was actually meaningless because the spill was complex but the question was formatted as a single cause question. At least two factors were visible from the narrative and others, such as why the bottle was there in the first place, were undoubtedly involved. A neutral question would be something like, "How did Jack's actions contribute to the event?"
I was torn...and am still mulling over my choice.
Mike knocked into the bottle. If there was no one there to catch it, it would have spilled anyway.
